article.headline: Kansas State 80, Wyoming 67
article.story: MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Most of Kansas State's players have been together for only four games. You couldn't tell it by the Wildcats' play against Wyoming, though. Kansas State showed off its chemistry with unselfish play in a 17-4 second-half run that gave the Wildcats an 80-67 victory over the Cowboys on Wednesday night. "For two or three minutes there, we looked like we have been playing together for about 10 years," sophomore forward Marques Hayden said. Jarrett Hart scored 19 points as Kansas State continued its best start in six years. After committing 12 turnovers in the first half, Kansas State had just six in the second half. But the real domination was on the boards, where Kansas State outrebounded the Cowboys 49-27. "The stat that has to be talked about is rebounding," coach Jim Wooldridge said. "That was a good sight for Kansas State basketball. That was significant in the game." Wyoming coach Steve McClain agreed. "It wasn't just our big guys. Our guards didn't get enough rebounds, because those big guys from Kansas State are physical guys," McClain said. Kansas State closed out the first half with a 10-0 run for a 33-25 lead and then went up 53-33 with 12:13 left in the game. Back-to-back 3-pointers by Jay Straight got Wyoming (2-2) within 10 points, but Hart hit a free throw and a 3-pointer to stop the rally. Hart's performance came on the heels of his game-winning 3-pointer in a 68-65 win over Gardner-Webb on Saturday. "It gives me a lot more confidence," Hart said. "But it's just one game. Next game I might not be the leading scorer." Tim Ellis had a double-double with 16 points and 10 rebounds for the Wildcats, and freshman Cartier Martin had 10 points in his first game. The NCAA suspended Martin for the first three games of the season for receiving improper benefits from a booster during his high school career, an infraction not related to Kansas State's recruitment of him. "He looked like he was nervous," Wooldridge said of Martin. "We saw glimpses of what he is capable of. He has a lot more minutes left this season." Hayden also had 10 points for the Wildcats, who are 4-0 for the first time since they opened the 1997-98 seasons with nine wins. Hayden added six assists and nine rebounds for Kansas State. "We did a heck of a job on defense," Hayden said. "We made a bucket and they are basically giving the ball back to us." Straight led the Cowboys with 17 points. Dion Sherrell added 13 points, Omoniyi Makun finished with 12 and Alex Dunn had 10.
